{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496784"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1419"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1419"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.7,0.01,0.09,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109433"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1419"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1419"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91802"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1582"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11351"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48374"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109433","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109433"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four day history of dyspnoea and palpitations. On examination she has an irregular heart rate of 120/min, blood pressure 118/72 mmHg and respiratory rate 18/min. An ECG shows an irregularly irregular rhythm and absent P waves. Her medical history includes type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["DC cardioversion","Rate control and anticoagulation with DOACs","Catheter ablation","Rate control and anticoagulation with warfarin","Rhythm control and anticoagulation with DOACs"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAtrial fibrillation (AF) can be managed in a number of ways. In this case the patient is haemodynamically stable with AF symptoms for more than 48 hours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen AF persists for more than 48 hours, then rate or rhythm control, with anticoagulation (as indicated by stroke and bleeding risk assessments such as CHA\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003EDS\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E-VA) is recommended. Rate control includes beta blockers or non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers. Rhythm control medications include sotalol, flecainide and amiodarone. Factors that favour rate control include persistent AF, less symptomatic, age \u0026gt;65 years, hypertension, and no history of heart failure. This patient exhibits many of these features and has no contraindications for anticoagulation with a DOAC; thus, \u003Cstrong\u003Erate control with DOAC anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E would be the appropriate next step in management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDOACs (e.g. apixaban, rivaroxaban) are preferred over \u003Cstrong\u003Ewarfarin\u003C/strong\u003E for anticoagulation unless the patient has a mechanical heart valve, rheumatic mitral stenosis and/or end-stage renal disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the onset is within 48 hours, \u003Cstrong\u003EDC cardioversion \u003C/strong\u003Ecan be used, as there is a low risk (due to inadequate time) of thrombus formation. Equally, if the patient is haemodynamically unstable then urgent DC cardioversion is needed regardless of the duration. In this case, although the patient is dyspneic, she shows no other signs of haemodynamic instability (e.g. hypotension, heart failure, angina, altered mental state, signs of shock) and therefore does not warrant this treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECatheter ablation\u003C/strong\u003E is typically reserved for symptomatic AF resistant to other anti-arrhythmic therapies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The basis of uncomplicated atrial fibrillation management is rate or rhythm control, thromboembolic risk assessment and prevention.","Direct oral anticoagulants are preferred over warfarin for most patients with non-valvular atrial fibrillation."],"references":["Brieger D, Amerena J, Attia J, Bajorek B, Chan KH, Connell C, et al. National Heart Foundation of Australia and the Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Australian Clinical Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Atrial Fibrillation 2018. 2018; 27(10): 1209-66. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30077228/","Li J, Gao M, Zhang M, Liu D, Li Z, Du J, Hou Y. Treatment of atrial fibrillation: a comprehensive review and practice guide. Cardiovasc J Afr. 2020 May/Jun 23;31(3):153-158. doi: 10.5830/CVJA-2019-064. Epub 2020 Mar 18. PMID: 32186324; PMCID: PMC8762786. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32186324/","Zamani P, Verdino RJ. Management of Atrial Fibrillation. J Intensive Care Med. 2015 Dec;30(8):484-98. doi: 10.1177/0885066614534603. Epub 2014 May 14. PMID: 24828991. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24828991/","Lacoste JL, Szymanski TW, Avalon JC, Kabulski G, Kohli U, Marrouche N, Singla A, Balla S, Jahangir A. Atrial Fibrillation Management: A Comprehensive Review with a Focus on Pharmacotherapy, Rate, and Rhythm Control Strategies. Am J Cardiovasc Drugs. 2022 Sep;22(5):475-496. doi: 10.1007/s40256-022-00529-6. Epub 2022 Mar 30. PMID: 35353353. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/35353353/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91802"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1419"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91802"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T09:08:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T18:33:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1419"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109433"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"Ge